observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our previous audit recommendation that Management:
a. Require the Inventory Committee to continuously make utmost effort to conduct a complete and detailed physical inventory of all the Municipality’s properties in accordance with the guidelines and procedures prescribed by COA Circular No. 2020-006 and submit the RPCPPE with complete details as required by NGAS for LGUs, Volume II;
b. Require the GSO and the Municipal Accountant to maintain updated PCs and PPELCs, respectively, per category on all PPE as recorded in the books of accounts, and continuously coordinate with each other in order to reconcile the discrepancies in the respective PPE accounts;
c. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to depreciate all PPEs annually in accordance with the regulations in order to reflect the accurate and reliable value of PPE in the FS; and
d. Make necessary adjustments for the noted erroneous recording of accounts, particularly those tangible items which meet the definition and recognition criteria of PPE but cost is below Fifty Thousand Pesos (P50,000.00). These items shall be accounted in the books of accounts as semi-expendable property.

We recommended that Management:
a. Demand immediate settlement/liquidation of the outstanding CAs especially from all AOs and employees still connected with the LGU, pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002;
b. Require the Municipal Accountant to strictly monitor the grant, utilization and liquidation of CAs and avoid granting additional cash advance unless the previous cash advance is first settled and a proper accounting thereof is made;
c. Initiate the appropriate legal actions/sanctions against those erring AOs/employees for continued non-compliance with the existing laws, rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of CAs; and
d. File a request to COA for authority to write-off and/or adjust the dormant or non-moving accounts as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2016-005. The request must be duly supported with the documents required in the said circular.

We reiterated our previous audit recommendations that Management require:
a. The GSO to prepare and submit duly accomplished RPCI within the prescribed period;
b. The GSO to consolidate weekly the RIS for which supplies and materials were issued using the SSMI and submit these documents to Accounting Unit for recording of expenses in the book of accounts;
c. The Municipal Accountant to discontinue recording supplies for stock as outright expenses. Instead, purchases of inventories for consumption or distribution should be properly recorded under the appropriate inventory accounts, with the corresponding consumption or distribution recognized as an expense upon receipt of the SSMI for a given period;
d. The Accounting Unit to maintain SLCs for each type of supplies to record all receipts and issuances; and
e. Both the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to conduct periodic reconciliation of their records and make adjustment, when necessary, to reflect the true balance of the Inventory Accounts in the FS.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
a. Adhere strictly to the accrual method of accounting for income derived from RPTs, in compliance with the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs;
b. Review the correctness of the accounting entries before approving the JEVs and recording thereof in the books of accounts;
c. Properly analyze, classify and record every transaction in the books in accordance with the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs; and
d. Make necessary adjusting entries for the aforementioned transactions to ensure fair presentation and reliability of the account balances in the FS.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the HRMO to formulate a uniform policy and procedures in the engagement of JO workers to ensure that the hiring process is free from bias and has a consistent basis for assigning wage rates to improve the existing system;
b. Engage the MRMO in the hiring process of JO personnel to ensure that candidates possess the necessary competencies and qualifications required for their assigned roles;
c. Delegate to each Department Head the responsibility of preparing the payroll for their respective JO personnel, ensuring that it is duly supported with accomplished DTRs and accomplishment reports;
d. Direct the Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking supporting documents and to exercise due diligence in verifying the completeness and accuracy of all supporting documents prior to the processing and release of payments; and
e. Submit justification on the noted deficiencies.

We recommended that Management:
a. Advise the Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Accountant to ascertain that all charges and payments under the LDRRMF align with the four thematic areas of disaster risk reduction and management and strictly adhere to the provisions of NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC Nos. 2013-1 and 2014-1;
b. Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the unexpended balance of Quick Response Fund (QRF) and Mitigation Fund (MF)-Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses (MOOE) be transferred to Special Trust Fund (STF) at the end of the year;
c. Direct the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction Management Officer (MDRRMO) to prepare the monthly report on utilization of Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management Fund (LDRRMF) in accordance with Annex B of COA Circular No. 2012-002;
d. Require the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Budget Officer and MDRRMO to conduct annual reconciliation of their respective records on the utilization of LDRRMF to avoid inconsistent balances on their reports and ensure that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted thereon accordingly;
e. Submit the lacking and appropriate supporting documents on the financial transactions listed in Annex A, as well as the unsubmitted DVs listed in Annex B; and
f. Submit justification on the noted deficiencies.

We recommended the Local Chief Executive, as Chairman of the LSB, to:
a. Direct the LSB to allocate SEF primarily to the expenses listed under Item 3.1 of the JC;
b. Require the submission of the Quarterly and Annual Reports using the SEF Budget Accountability Form No. 1 (Annex B) on SEF utilization, as prepared by the Local Accountant, to the concerned offices—DepEd Central Office (through appropriate channels), Local Sanggunian, and Regional Offices of DBM and DILG;
c. Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to submit a certified statement regarding the actual SEF income (for the immediately preceding fiscal year and for the first two quarters of the current year) and the estimated SEF income for the last two quarters of the current year not later than July 15 of the current year; and
d. Submit explanation/justification on the aforementioned deficiencies.

We recommended that Management:
a. Ensure that the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer immediately release the amount due to province and to various barangays of the Municipality;
b. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to evaluate the balances of barangay counterparts and make the necessary adjusting entries for the amounts whose intended infrastructure projects were already completed;
c. Direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to maintain records and SL for each barangay to facilitate the release of RPT and CTC within the prescribed period; and
d. Require them to adhere strictly to the guidelines relative to the prompt release of the barangay shares from realty taxes stated under Section 271 (d) of the Local Government Code in the ensuing years.

We recommended that Management direct the GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) to:
a. Conduct an updated gender sensitivity analysis and implement programs and activities that specifically address gender issues based on the results of the analysis;
b. Reconsider incorporating the listed PPAs into other funds aside from GAD Fund, such as GF, TF, and other special purpose fund;
c. Submit the attachments of GAD AR as mentioned in Item 4.C.8.5 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, along with the lacking supporting documents listed in Annex A; and
d. Submit explanation on the noted deficiencies.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Facilitate the immediate transfer of the completed projects to its respective appropriate PPE accounts in accordance with Section 50 of the Manual on NGAS;
Work back to trace the entries of the dormant CIP accounts and ascertain the status of the projects recorded;
Make the necessary adjustments to correct the actual balance of the CIP accounts, PPE accounts, the corresponding Depreciation Expense accounts and other related accounts affected by the non-transfer of completed projects and errors committed in the recording of the CIP; and
Recognize construction in progress based on progress billings and other acceptable and appropriate supporting documents which will properly substantiate its balance.

We recommended that Management:
Require the driver to prepare a Driver’s Trip Ticket prior to travel and require all authorized passengers to affix their signature/s on the trip tickets. Otherwise, refrain from allowing the government vehicle to be used for travel in the absence of the same;
Prepare and submit the Monthly Report of Official Travels and Fuel Consumption at the end of each month to the Auditor, for verification; 
Require concerned official to submit the required lacking supporting documents; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to exercise due diligence in the verification of the propriety and completeness of supporting documents as well as in posting of entries in the Journals and to faithfully adhere to Section 4 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 77-61 dated September 26, 1977.

We recommended that Management require:
The GSO to prepare and submit duly accomplished RPCI;
Concerned Department Heads to prepare the required RIS for the supplies requisitioned and the GSO to consolidate weekly the RIS for which supplies and materials were issued using the SSMI;  
The Municipal Accountant to properly record the purchases of inventories for consumption or distribution in the appropriate inventory accounts and the consumption or distribution thereof as expense, upon receipt of SSMI of a given period;
The Accounting Unit to maintain SLC and the GSO to maintain SC as required in both offices; and
Both the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to conduct periodic reconciliation of their records and make adjustments, when necessary, to reflect the true balance of the Inventory Accounts in the FS.

We recommended that Management:
Enjoin the LDRRMO to exert more effort in implementing actions and measures pertaining to all aspects of disaster risk reduction and management towards building a disaster-resilient LGU and communities;
Closely monitor the implementation of all PPAs under the LDRRMF to facilitate corrective action, if any, and the timely reprogramming and reallocation of the fund for its optimum utilization;
Instruct the LDRRMO to prepare and submit monthly Report on the Sources and Utilization of LDRRMF with complete and sufficient information on time and facilitate monitoring of the accomplishment vis-à-vis the targeted projects for effective and efficient utilization of the fund; and
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to maintain separate RAAOs for LDRRMF in compliance with Section 5.1.4 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 to facilitate proper control and monitoring of appropriations, allotments and obligations under the said fund.

We recommended that Management:
Require the concerned officials to submit the required lacking supporting documents and other related procurement guidelines; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to exercise due diligence in the verification of the propriety and completeness of supporting documents and to faithfully adhere to Section 4 (6) of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular 2012-001;

We reiterated the following to Management:
Require the Inventory Committee to continuously exert utmost effort to conduct a complete and detailed physical inventory of all the LGU’s properties in accordance with the new guidelines and procedures prescribed by COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31 2020, prepare and submit, within the deadlines set, the RPCPPE together with the RPCRNS of the LGU;
Instruct the GSO to prepare and maintain the Local Road Inventory Map and Property Cards for each type of properties as basis for reconciliation with the PPE accounts with the accounting records;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain, in relation to the local road networks of the LGU, LRNLC, including the regular property ledger cards, also as basis for reconciliation with the General Ledger account balances and with the property records; and
Require the GSO and Municipal Accountant to make a final reconciliation of their respective records and avail the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, strictly in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006, particularly on the disposition and derecognition of non-existing/missing PPE and adjust the books accordingly, in order to come up with a reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended that Management instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Prepare and submit liquidation reports of outstanding fund transfers received from various agencies which purposes were already completed, and return any unspent amount and henceforth, strictly adhere with the provisions of Section 4 of COA Circular No. 94-013 dated December 13, 1994 and Section 3.1.2 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated June 14, 2012. Likewise, record in the books of accounts those FTs that were already utilized and liquidation reports had been submitted to source agencies;
If the disposition of the unspent/unutilized amount is not provided in the MOA, Trust Agreement or Memorandum of Understanding, the agency may, at their option, utilize the said amount by sending a letter to the source agency requesting approval to transfer the unexpended balance to the General Fund (Section 3.2 of COA Circular 2012-001);
Fast track the implementation of the fund transfers since the resources are readily available, and in order not to deprive the Municipality of the programs, projects and activities (PPAs) where the funds are intended for; and
Reconcile the Due to NGAs account and take up the necessary correcting/adjusting entries for fair presentation in the Financial Statements.

We recommended and reiterated that Management:
Strictly comply with the rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances in accordance with the provisions provided under COA Circular No. 97-002;
Issue demand letters to officials and employees, who have outstanding cash advances as of December 31, 2021, especially those who are still in the active service, copies of which are to be submitted to the Auditor with proof of service and dated to enforce settlement of unliquidated cash advances;
Prioritize the institution of administrative and/or legal action against the former OIC-MT on account of his undeposited collections, unliquidated cash advances and other offenses committed in the performance of his duties; and
File request for authority to write-off dormant or long outstanding unliquidated cash advances, if necessary, to the Office of the Auditor, pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

We recommended that Management require:
The Property/Supply Officer to prepare and submit the duly accomplished RPCI;
The Accountant to properly record the purchases of inventories for consumption or distribution in the appropriate inventory accounts and the consumption or distribution thereof as expense, upon receipt of SSMI of a given period;
The Accounting Unit to maintain Supplies Ledger Cards and the Local Treasury Unit or the General Services Office to maintain Stock Cards as required in both their offices; and
Both the Accountant and the Supply Officer to conduct periodic reconciliation of their records and make adjustment when necessary, to reflect the true balance of the Inventory Accounts in the Financial Statements.

We recommended that Management require:
The BAC Secretariat to consolidate the PPMP included in the budget proposal into an indicative APP and the BAC to make a final recommendation of the appropriate procurement modality of identified PPA in the PPMP to the HoPE and submit reqularly the required APP to the Audit Team;
The Supply and Property Division to consolidate his purchase request with other purchase request of similar items and perform activities pertaining to the mode of procurement to be used for the requested supplies and materials before making any purchases;
The concerned official to submit explanation/justification and the lacking supporting documents for the deficiencies noted; and
The Accountant to exercise due diligence in the verification of the propriety and completeness of supporting documents and to faithfully adhere to Section 4 of PD No. 1445 and other related laws, rules and regulations.

That the Office of the Municipal Accountant give utmost attention to the preparation and submission of the required bank reconciliation statements pursuant to Section 474 of Republic Act (RA) No. 7160 and COA Circular No.96-011 dated October 2, 1996 and substantiate the unreconciled difference substantially amounting to approximately ₱14.92 million;
That the OIC-Municipal Treasurer prepare and maintain updated cash books and reconcile the same with the Accounting records; and
Any error and reconciling item discovered in the reconciliation process must accordingly be adjusted in the respective records which need correction/revision, to arrive at a correct and reliable cash in bank balance.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Submit the supporting documents on all the recorded obligations in the Accounts Payable account;
Exert effort to prepare and maintain complete SLs for the said account under all funds;
If the balances could not be substantiated after all remedies are resorted to, request for the write-off of account balances in accordance with the prescribed procedures; and
Ensure that all obligations are duly supported with complete documents to prove the validity of the claims before recording it in the books as Accounts Payable or any liability account.

We reiterated and recommended the following:
The LGU must create a special trust fund account to which the unexpended LDRRMF must accrue;
The Municipal Accountant and the Budget Officer must ensure that the unexpended balance of QRF and MF-MOOE for each year be timely transferred at year-end;
The Municipal Accountant, Budget Officer and MDRRM Officer must immediately account for the unexpended LDRRM funds from CY 2014 to CY 2019 and submit a report thereon; and
The Accounting Office must coordinate with the Budget Office to determine how much of the ₱4.45 million could still be transferred to the special trust fund considering the remaining available cash and priority obligations to be paid thereof, rule out the unexpended balance beyond the last five years, reconcile their records and obtain the correct amount of the unexpended balances and effect the transfer immediately.

We recommended that Management:
Expedite the completion/updating of the 10-Year Municipal SWM Plan for approval by the NSWMC to serve as guide for the efficient management of solid waste generated within the Municipality’s jurisdiction;
Prioritize SWM programs and projects by providing/allocating enough budget for their full implementation;
Encourage and provide needed assistance to the remaining 12 barangays to establish their own MRFs for the collection, segregation, recycling of biodegradable, recyclable, compostable and reusable wastes; and
Exert continuous effort in preserving and protecting the environment by implementing the environmental laws as mandated under RA No. 9003.

We recommended and reiterated to the Management that:
The ICO-Municipal Treasurer must have all undeposited collections as of December 31, 2017 deposited immediately intact and in full with the authorized government depository bank;

b. The ICO-Municipal Treasurer must stop immediately the practice of holding large amount of undeposited collections;

c. The Accounting Office be required to ensure regular reconciliation of balances and prepare subsidiary ledgers for all accountable officers to properly and correctly determine respective accountabilities; and

d. Appropriate administrative and/or legal actions be instituted against the accountable officers for non-compliance with the above-cited regulations, if warranted.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Inventory Committee to completely fill out the information on the whereabouts and conditions of all properties physically counted to determine other unserviceable PPE items. The Inventory Committee must recommend them for disposal while the properties still carry their respective salvage value and submit a written report to the GSO of the result of the actual physical inventory conducted so the latter could undertake appropriate and feasible remedies for any deficiencies noted;
Require the GSO to prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties and file an application for disposal through the Local Chief Executive with the Office of the Audit Team Leader, by conducting first an appraisal of the properties for disposal in accordance with the Manual on Appraisal of Government Properties except Real Properties and Works of Art;
Any losses of government property determined during the physical count must be reported and accountability thereof must be determined. Future losses of properties by any accountable officer or person in custody must be properly and immediately disseminated to concerned offices. The appropriate request for relief from accountability must be requested from the Commission on Audit within the period prescribed by existing rules and regulations, together with the supporting documentary requirements, which would include the basic notice of loss, report stating the facts and circumstances of the loss, valuations and other necessary details or documents; and
When the LGU plans to construct a new building or structure where there is an existing lot and building, it must carefully consider two options: (1) Rehabilitation of the existing building or structure, and (2) complete demolition of the existing building or structure and construction of a new one in its stead. However, when the LGU considers pursuing the latter option, there must be a showing that said option is highly recommended by the Municipal Engineer considering various factors such as degree and structural defect, building standards, and higher cost of rehabilitation, among others, and COA must be informed of such action for its review and evaluation.

We recommended that Management,
a. Once again, require the Inventory Committee to conduct the annual physical count of all its property, plant and equipment and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment to the Office of the Auditor;
b. Evaluate the Agency’s property and supply management system, identify lapses therein and correct the same the soonest;
c. Direct the General Services Officer and Municipal Accountant to maintain the respective complete property records required from their offices; and
d. Conduct reconciliation with their respective records and work on tracing any reconciling items.
